You actually don&#39;t have to reverse the array at all. Just remove items one by one alternating between the beginning and the end.

```
$array = [&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;c&#39;, &#39;d&#39;, &#39;e&#39;];

$result = [];
$takeFromBeginning = true;
while(count($array))
{
    if($takeFromBeginning) {
        $result[] = array_shift($array);
    } else {
        $result[] = array_pop($array);
    }

    $takeFromBeginning = !$takeFromBeginning;
}

print_r($result);

```

If the result for `$array = [&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;c&#39;, &#39;d&#39;, &#39;e&#39;];` should be `aebdc` you could use a loop with the [modulo](https://www.php.net/manual/en/language.operators.arithmetic.php) `%` operator and index either from the left or the right side into the `$array`.

For example:


    $array = [&#39;a&#39;, &#39;b&#39;, &#39;c&#39;, &#39;d&#39;, &#39;e&#39;];
    
    function customReverse($array) {
        $reversedArray = [];
        $count = count($array);
        for ($i = 0; $i &lt; count($array); $i++) {
            $reversedArray[] = $i % 2 === 0 ? $array[$i / 2] : $array[$count - ($i / 2)];
        }
        return $reversedArray;
    }
    
    print_r(customReverse($array));

Output  


    Array
    (
        [0] =&gt; a
        [1] =&gt; e
        [2] =&gt; b
        [3] =&gt; d
        [4] =&gt; c
    )

[Php demo](https://3v4l.org/LjRJD)

